\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing single
Competitions for Social mobility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
As far as market principles can work, status and mobility have a key role
 to play in economic development.
 The core of Adam Smith's arguments is that economic progress can be achieved
 by letting an exchange between the rich and poor thrive.
 In the world Adam Smith lived, trinkets could be turned into bread
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WicksteedCommonSense"

\end_inset

.
 From this point of view, more spending on a conspicuous item would benefit
 the society as a whole - since the money obtained from the rich on the
 item could potentially fund employment and other opportunities.
 Electricity would for example be a model item for this purpose in Africa
 - an item whose consumption can drive the expansion of power plants and
 make electricity cheaper.
 More spending on signaling goods does not appear to be a social waste from
 this perspective.
 However, not all marketable goods are as desirable as electricity and there
 may be goals more desirable than what the said exchange can provide.
 Unlike in the Western world - where the differences between the rich and
 poor have already been reduced to a level that this exchange could not
 be made lucrative to the poor any more
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In other words, the price of luxuries has exceeded the opportunity cost
 to the rest of the society 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - the basic needs for the masses haven't been addressed in the developing
 world.
 While one should expect the exchange between rich and poor to draw the
 masses out of poverty in Africa, there are limits to such success in the
 developing countries.
 The essential goods often lack a market in the developing countries and
 since marketable goods often create needs on their own, the development
 of market for conspicuous goods may prevent the status competitions from
 achieving the goals of social welfare.
 The way societies are structured, anything available to the richer sections
 of the society can easily become a status good and thus the possibility
 of a social waste due to spending on status goods cannot be ruled out in
 the developing countries either.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
These limitations of status competitions are largely because of weak institution
s in the developing countries - which have followed their own paths to economic
 development while achieving goals of nationalism.
 The developing countries now face the problem of institutions not being
 strong enough to establish the exchange between the rich and the poor or
 to let it thrive.
 In the new urban settings in Africa, both tribal identities and the hierarchies
 formed through education, money or industrial assets now contribute to
 status competitions.
 While this development can encourage institutions of money and education
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Status differences can spur consumption on status goods - and can be particularl
y relevant to social welfare - for example - if education turns out to be
 a status good.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the status competitions in absence of welfare-centered institutions can
 limit themselves to markets not developed enough to undertake severe scarcities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
The relationship between education, urban developments, income levels and
 tribal identities is difficult to assess without access to the microdata
 on tribal identities and regional migration.
 In absence of this data (as is the case with LSMS used in the study), we
 can consider other proxies that may be correlated with social identities
 (e.g.
 family income levels, language spoken, locality etc.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The LSMS data is available to enumeration-area levels in the crowded regions
 (which are over-represented in the samples).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ).
 Still, the measurement error for variables in any claimed relationship
 between identity and purchasing power in Africa can be severe - due to
 i) a bulky informal sector (which may have expanded due to recent economic
 developments), ii) expansions in the areas of micro-credit as well as mass
 education 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DolanBoP"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MeagherNigeria"

\end_inset

 and iii) the complicated changes in identities themselves - which are homogenis
ing with the expansion of internal trade (investments from South Africa
 and Western countries have for example are known to have expanded significantly
 in Tanzania).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current study so far considers only the district level residence and
 the primary spoken language as the demographic factors that may contribute
 to status consumption.
 The differences between economic classes that can provide a measure of
 the movements in social mobility are modeled as the change in permanent
 income of the consumers (proxied by total expenditure on items in the survey).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset VSpace medskip*
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing single
Wealth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Ultimately, wealth is the strongest indicator of status.
 Status related consumption exists because i) wealth is often not directly
 visible and ii) those in the middle-rank of wealth might want to indicate
 more status than is indicated by their real wealth.
 This makes status goods universally relevant for consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset VSpace medskip*
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing single
Supply of an item
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
In simple terms, a signaling product indicates the buyer's status to the
 immediate surroundings.
 Status being a sociological phenomenon, it is non-trivial to classify a
 good as a signaling good.
 If for example, only the rich could afford electricity in a society, electricit
y may not appear as a signaling product for most of the population.
 From the point of view of consumption, a good being used by a smaller and
 richer part of the population has less significance than a good used by
 the majority of the population.
 Items consumed by more people may carry more significance in deciding whether
 a good is a status good or not
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A regression with quantities consumed as dependent variable would bear more
 significance for items consumed by more people.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - however, one must also consider the supply of the item and the permanent
 income of the consumer before declaring an item more status bearing than
 the other.
 When an item is in limited supply, only those consumers with higher purchasing
 power (or those who must pass some other barrier) would have access to
 it.
 For example, if electricity is not available throughout the country, then
 only those with higeher income or with residence in certain areas (where
 there is electricity) can have their signaling needs fulfilled with the
 item.
 Hence, when expenditure on the item is limited to the richer sections of
 society, then the item is a status good merely through being a statement
 of wealth
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The difference between concepts of physical and social scarcity described
 by Hirsch
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"

\end_inset

 is discarded in this approach.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, electricity would be considered a status item in our study -
 simply because its low supply indicates richness explicitly.
 Another consequence of this observation is that the supply of an item can
 be used in a selection equation to reduce the bias in the zero consumption
 of an item (such as electricity).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset VSpace medskip*
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing single
Bandwagon effect
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Other than the price of the item in the market or other barriers to distribution
 of the desired item, what characterises a typical status improving commodity
 is the tendency of the consumers to flock towards the item.
 The demand for a status item is enhanced by the popularity of the item.
 Newly introduced goods thus often create a market of their own - a mechanism
 often accentuated by the advertising effects.
 This 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bandwagon
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 effect is essential to indicating one's social standing (modeled as rank
 by Corneo et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
As a crude way to detect this tendency to flock towards an item (i.e.
 the bandwagon effect), we rely on time-series change of the budget share
 (analysis of elasticities) of the item to see how sensitive the budget
 share of the item is to time, income and supply.
 The equilibrium consumption values can shift when a higher supply is provided
 (more electrical power plants or cheaper alternative energy would reduce
 the budget share on electricity).
 If the budget share of electricity increases then we may conclude that
 people may be flocking to the commodity (after accounting for considering
 income effects)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This measure of flocking is termed as bandwagon effect in the study.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
This method of classification can provide some (not all) candidates for
 status goods - but as long as everybody wants higher status it can be argued
 that all status goods would exhibit a change in budget share with respect
 to supply (a snob item - where more abundance causes disinterest would
 report a decrease in budget share - thus for items that are available only
 to the rich are likely to become snob items)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hirsch considers 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

overuse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as a criterion for signaling items i.e.
 when individuals use a commodity too much, its signaling qualities decline.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This classification can help explore how availability of new industrial
 goods can transform expenditure on status items over a given period of
 time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset VSpace medskip*
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing single
Urban-rural differences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
The African context presents a unique opportunity to study the demand for
 industrial goods.
 The outreach and resources of the governmental institutions in African
