\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
A study by Kaus(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KausSA"

\end_inset

) considers a black-dummy and coloured-dummy in regression of visible consumptio
n against demographic, time, permanent income and household characteristics.
 Starting with no controls(I)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family typewriter
lm(lnvis~black_dummy+coloured_dummy)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
Regressors and instruments in implementation of ivreg in R-toolbox AER are
 specified in a formula with two parts on the right-hand side.
 The specification - used in this note - can be either of the form - 
\family typewriter
y ~ ex + en | ex + in 
\family default
or as 
\family typewriter
y ~ ex + en | .
 - en +in 
\family default
(where 
\family typewriter
ex
\family default
 is the set of exogenous variables, 
\family typewriter
en
\family default
 is the set of endogenous variables and 
\family typewriter
in 
\family default
the set of instruments) .
 The latter is the notation used throughout in this section.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (with black-dummy and coloured-dummy), the coefficients for coloured and
 black are negative (i.e.
 black and coloured social groups spend less on visible consumption than
 the white population).
 However, these coefficients flip signs after adding income controls(II)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family typewriter
lm(lnvis~black_dummy+coloured_dummy+ lninc) 
\family default
- where lninc is log(income_household_head).
 Notice that only log of income level is found significant when used along
 side with income-level-cubic and income level.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
The coefficients for black and coloured groups are even higher when expenditure
 is added(III)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family typewriter
lm(lnvis~black_dummy+coloured_dummy+ lninc+lnpinc) 
\family default
- where lnpinc is log of total expenditure (which itself is a proxy for
 permanent income)
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The endogeneity of total expenditure requires instrumentation - Kaus uses
 instruments suggested by Charles, Roussanov and Hurst - including positive-inco
me-dummy, cube-of-income-level, dummies for under-secondary-education, secondary
-education and degree-education.
 Kaus then performs two 2SLS regressions - one with income controls and
 total-expenditure as control variables
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family typewriter
ivreg(lnvis~black_dummy+coloured_dummy+ lninc+ lnpinc | .
 - lnpinc + cbinc + lsecd + secd + degree)
\family default
 - where lsecd,secd and degree are education dummies and cbinc is income-level-c
ubic.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and the other with education-dummies as control variables (while still
 using instruments)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family typewriter
ivreg(lnvis~black_dummy+coloured_dummy+ lnpinc +lsecd | .
 - lnpinc + cbinc+lninc +incpsv
\family default
) 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The instrumentation thus performed (Specification IV in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "resresults-1"

\end_inset

) results in lower coefficients for the black and coloured dummies for both
 regressions.
\end_layout

